The mobilization effort also included the creation of agencies such as the Office of War Mobilization (OWM) and the Office of War Mobilization and Reconversion (OWMR), which coordinated industrial production and labor allocation. These agencies expanded federal control over the economy beyond New Deal levels but did so primarily through subsidies, tax breaks, and contracts guaranteeing profits to businesses rather than direct coercion ([Encyclopedia.com, n.d.](https://www.encyclopedia.com/economics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/world-war-ii-and-ending-depression)).

### 2.2 Labor Mobilization and Employment Surge

WWII created millions of jobs both in the military and in war-related industries. Over 12 million Americans were drafted or enlisted in the armed forces, and a comparable number worked in defense industries ([SidmartinBio, 2019](https://www.sidmartinbio.org/how-did-world-war-2-end-the-great-depression/)). This massive labor demand eliminated unemployment virtually overnight, reducing it from 14.6% in 1940 to 1.2% by 1944 ([Encyclopedia.com, n.d.](https://www.encyclopedia.com/economics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/world-war-ii-and-ending-depression)).

The war also led to the inclusion of women, African Americans, and other previously marginalized groups in the workforce in unprecedented numbers, further expanding the labor pool and contributing to economic growth ([Encyclopedia.com, n.d.](https://www.encyclopedia.com/economics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/world-war-ii-and-ending-depression)).

### 2.3 Industrial Production and Economic Output

The U.S. became the "arsenal of democracy," producing about 40% of all war goods worldwide by 1944 ([Encyclopedia.com, n.d.](https://www.encyclopedia.com/economics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/world-war-ii-and-ending-depression)). This industrial boom led to a doubling of the GNP between 1939 and 1944, from $91 billion to $214 billion. Factories were retooled for continuous 24/7 production, requiring more workers and materials, which further stimulated economic activity ([Brainly.com, 2016](https://brainly.com/question/1264029)).

### 2.4 Keynesian Economic Principles and Deficit Spending

The wartime economic mobilization corroborated the Keynesian argument that deficit spending could stimulate economic growth. The government ran massive deficits to finance the war, which increased aggregate demand and economic output ([Encyclopedia.com, n.d.](https://www.encyclopedia.com/economics/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/world-war-ii-and-ending-depression)). This experience influenced postwar fiscal policy and reinforced New Deal liberalism's focus on macroeconomic management.

### 2.5 Postwar Economic Transition and Deregulation

While wartime spending and mobilization ended the Depression, some economists argue that the true restoration of prosperity occurred after WWII, when government spending and regulation sharply declined. Between 1945 and 1947, government spending fell from 42% of GDP to 14%, and many wartime regulatory agencies were dismantled ([Forbes, 2013](https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterferrara/2013/11/30/the-great-depression-was-ended-by-the-end-of-world-war-ii-not-the-start-of-it/)). This deregulation and tax reduction helped transition the economy to peacetime prosperity.

---

## 3. Alternative Perspectives and Critiques

### 3.1 War Spending as a Mask, Not a Cure

Some historians and economists contend that the wartime government spending only masked the underlying economic problems of the Great Depression. The national debt grew from $49 billion in 1941 to $260 billion by 1945, raising concerns about the sustainability of such fiscal policies ([Reference.com, 2020](https://www.reference.com/history/did-great-depression-end-2aa9f35a22788aa7)).

### 3.2 The End of the New Deal and Postwar Prosperity

Richard W. Fulmer and others argue that WWII did not end the Depression but rather ended the New Deal. According to this view, the true economic recovery and prosperity came after the war, driven by reduced government spending, tax cuts, and deregulationâ€”not by wartime deficit spending ([Fee.org, 2009](https://fee.org/articles/world-war-ii-ended-the-great-depression/); [Forbes, 2013](https://www.forbes.com/sites/peterferrara/2013/11/30/the-great-depression-was-ended-by-the-end-of-world-war-ii-not-the-start-of-it/)).

### 3.3 The Role of Private Sector and Postwar Reforms

Postwar economic growth is also attributed to pro-market reforms and increased consumer confidence rather than government intervention alone. For example, in West Germany and Japan, economic miracles were driven by market-oriented reforms encouraged by the U.S. rather than direct war spending ([Centre for Policy Studies, n.d.](https://cps.org.uk/research/history-repeating-the-lessons-of-the-postwar-recovery/)).

---

## 4. Synthesis and Opinion

The evidence overwhelmingly supports that WWII played a critical role in ending the Great Depression, primarily through massive government spending, labor mobilization, and industrial production that sharply increased aggregate demand and employment. The war effort effectively eliminated unemployment by creating millions of military and defense-related jobs, while industrial output surged to unprecedented levels.

However, it is important to recognize that the war did not "cure" the Depression in a traditional sense but rather shifted the economy into a wartime footing that was unsustainable in peacetime. The postwar period, characterized by sharp reductions in government spending, deregulation, and tax cuts, was essential in transitioning the economy to lasting prosperity. This suggests that while WWII was the catalyst for ending the Depression, the structural reforms and economic policies implemented after the war were equally crucial.

Thus, WWII ended the Great Depression through a combination of:

- **Wartime mobilization** that created jobs and increased production,
- **Government deficit spending** that stimulated aggregate demand,
- **Postwar economic reforms** that restored market mechanisms and consumer confidence.

This nuanced understanding reconciles the Keynesian view of deficit spending with the classical emphasis on market-driven recovery.

